"American cheese" is spozed to be, SPOZED to be, a mild cheddar with natural yellow coloring from annato, usually made from whole milk, maybe with a bit of cream added to boost the fat content. The higher fat content makes it melt more easily and consistently for recipes. That is what "American cheese" is spoze 2b. The name is put onto all manner of inedible synthetic cheese-colored plastic product wrapped in individual plastic envelopes that smell of chemicals. But American cheese can be good and very edible, if you buy the non-crap version.

Or you could use the "processed cheese product" that comes in the foil-wrapped bricks inside a brightly colored cardboard box. That stuff used to be all cheese. It was is about half cream cheese by weight, with Swiss cheese and cheddar added, all combined by machine and cast in waxy blobs. It's got a really high fat content, which makes it really easy to work with for things like nachos or mac-n-cheese. Since around 2000 it's thickened with powdered milk and whey protein concentrate, which is why they have to call it "cheese food" or "cheese blend product" instead of just "cheese." I will admit to liking it in mac-n-cheese because it melts so nicely when stirred into a hot bechamel sauce. You can also simmer the pasta in milk--use elbow macaroni, and cook it in a double boiler with 25% greater volume of milk than pasta--for about half an hour, and stir the shredded cheese product directly into it.
